    {
      "id": "triangle",
      "name": "The Atlantic Triangle Trade",
      "subtitle": "Goods, enslaved people, and raw materials · 16th–19th c.",
      "unit": "voyages (relative)",
      "author": "Globe Genius",
      "version": "1.0",
      "yearFrom": 1514,
      "yearTo": 1866,
      "tags": [
        "history",
        "trade",
        "migration"
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "id": "ts1",
          "label": "SlaveVoyages — Trans-Atlantic Slave Trade Database",
          "url": "https://www.slavevoyages.org"
        }
      ],
      "scenes": [
        {
          "id": "sc1",
          "name": "Outward passage",
          "text": "European ships carry manufactured goods — textiles, metalware, guns — south to the West African coast.",
          "camera": {
            "rx": 8,
            "ry": -28,
            "zoom": 1
          },
          "flowIds": [
            "tt1",
            "tt2",
            "tt3"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "sc2",
          "name": "The Middle Passage",
          "text": "Enslaved Africans are transported across the Atlantic under brutal conditions. Roughly 12.5 million people were embarked over the trade’s duration.",
          "camera": {
            "rx": 30,
            "ry": -10,
            "zoom": 1.05
          },
          "flowIds": [
            "tt4",
            "tt5",
            "tt6",
            "tt7"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "sc3",
          "name": "Return passage",
          "text": "Sugar, tobacco, cotton and rum flow back to European ports, completing the triangle.",
          "camera": {
            "rx": 35,
            "ry": -32,
            "zoom": 1
          },
          "flowIds": [
            "tt8",
            "tt9",
            "tt10",
            "tt11"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "writeup": "<h2>The Atlantic triangle</h2><p>From the 16th to the 19th century, European ships carried manufactured goods to West Africa, enslaved people across the <i>Middle Passage</i> to the Americas, and colonial raw materials back to Europe.</p><p>The darker bands mark the Middle Passage routes.</p>",
